
---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About Me"
	description="A little about who I am and what I do"
	pubDate={new Date('August 08 2021')}
	heroImage="/blog-placeholder-about.jpg"
>
	<p>
		I’m the kind of person who would rather figure something out than wait for someone else to fix it.
		I work nights, which means most of my projects happen when the rest of the world is asleep and
		things are quiet enough to actually think. That’s when I build, test, break things, and usually
		fix them again before sunrise.
	</p>

	<p>
		I spend a lot of time working with systems, networks, and anything that lets me take control of
		how things run instead of relying on whatever default someone else decided was “good enough.”
		If something can be improved, I’ll probably end up digging into it just to see how far I can push it.
	</p>

	<p>
		Most of what I build is practical. Tools that make things faster, setups that are more reliable,
		or small changes that remove daily annoyances. I’m not interested in complicated for the sake of
		it. If it doesn’t make life easier, it’s not worth keeping.
	</p>

	<p>
		I’ve learned the hard way that every “simple upgrade” comes with tradeoffs. More features usually
		mean more maintenance, more points of failure, and more time spent fixing things that used to
		work fine. These days, I keep things as simple as possible and only add complexity when there’s
		a real reason for it.
	</p>

	<p>
		At the end of the day, I like systems that just work. Quiet, stable, predictable. If it runs in
		the background and never needs attention, that’s a win.
	</p>
</Layout>
